
==>A package in Node.js contains all the files you need for a module. 
==> Modules are JavaScript libraries you can include in your project.
==>npm is the Node package manager for Node.js. It also manages downloads of dependencies (third party)of your project.
==>npm init => to create "package.json".
==> When we install a package 
    * dependency object added in the package.json file 
    * new folder created node_modules

==>The package.json file is kind of a manifest for your project.
==>dependencies: sets a list of npm packages installed as dependencies

Semantic Versioning X.Y.Z ==> 
* the first digit is the major version(Mab be break the code or API) when you make incompatible API changes
* the second digit is the minor version(Does not break the API),when you add functionality in a backward-compatible
manner
* the third digit is the patch version(when you make backward-compatible bug fixes)

==> when we run npm update npm sets some rules we can use in package.json file to chose which version it can update ower packages to
==> when we run npm update node chackes the character infornt of the virsion 
==>"^0.13.0" when run npm it can update to 0.13.1 or 0.14.2 NOT to 1.14.0.
==>~: if you write ~0.13.0 when running npm update it can update to patch releases: 0.13.1 is ok, but 0.14.0 is not.
==> "0.13.0" when run npm it can update to the current virsion 

